## Using Rules in This Project

### Core Rules (This File)
This file contains universal rules that apply across all contexts. Keep these minimal and applicable to any project type.

### Modular Rules (.cursor/rules/)
For more specific guidance, use modular rules in `.cursor/rules/`. These are focused rules that can:
- Target specific file types (via glob patterns)
- Be manually invoked when needed
- Keep context focused and token-efficient

**Learn more:** `@.cursor/rules/README.md` - Complete guide to modular rules system

## Universal Coding Principles

### Documentation
- Document your code appropriately for your language/framework
- Explain "why" not just "what"
- Keep documentation up-to-date with code changes

### Code Quality
- Follow your language's best practices
- Use type safety when available
- Write clear, maintainable code
- Handle errors appropriately

### AI Collaboration Best Practices

**Be Specific:** Provide clear, detailed instructions
- ❌ "Fix the bug"
- ✅ "Fix the authentication error where tokens expire prematurely"

**Provide Context:** Use @ references to give relevant context
- `@filename.ext` - Reference specific files
- `@folder/` - Reference directories
- `@docs/` - Reference documentation
- `@codebase` - Search across the codebase

**Iterate Incrementally:** Break large tasks into smaller steps

**Review AI Output:** Always review and test AI-generated code

